  "body": "## The problem\r\n\r\nThe [`polymod` page says](https://docs.perl6.org/routine/polymod)\r\n\r\n> Returns a sequence of mod results corresponding to the divisors in @mods. The divisors are given from smallest \"unit\" to the largest\r\n\r\nHowever,\r\n\r\n    say 57.polymod(1,2,5,10,20,50);  # OUTPUT: «(0 1 3 5 0 0 0)␤»  \r\n    say 57.polymod(50,20,10,5,2,1);  # OUTPUT: «(7 1 0 0 0 0 0)␤»\r\n\r\nThey simply issue mods in the same order they are given in the argument. In fact, the examples use sometimes increasing units, some times decreasing.\r\n\r\n## Suggestions\r\n\r\n[Here is the code for `Int`](https://github.com/rakudo/rakudo/blob/eb6656b876867eb010504a4423823f527d259b74/src/core/Int.pm6#L105-L135) and the code for Num is similar. ",
